{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2026-04-20T19:37:59.142532+00:00", "modified": "2026-04-22T16:44:31.479960+00:00", "id": 19670385, "conceptrecid": "19670384", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19670385", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.19670384", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.19670385", "metadata": {"title": "Explaining variation in Brazil nut fruit production", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19670385", "publication_date": "2007", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) Brazil nut is widely recognized as the cornerstone of the Amazonian extractive economy. Tight linkages between Brazil nut production, regional income, and intact mature forests have thrust this species into focus as a key component of Amazonian conservation and income generation strategies. Nonetheless, a comprehensive synthesis of factors explaining Brazil nut fruit production variation is lacking. We aimed to address this knowledge gap, asking: (1) What are the rates and annual variation of Bertholletia excelsa fruit production at individual and population levels? (2) What factors explain B. excelsa production variation, focusing on spatial and temporal variables, diameter at breast height (dbh), crown attributes, liana loads, and soil attributes? and (3) Does liana cutting affect fruit production? Our model explained 73% of the variability in fruit production by 140 trees over 5 years. Dbh alone explained &gt;50%, and trees in the middle diameter range (100 cm dbh &lt; 150 cm) produced best. Top-producing trees were loosely grouped spatially. Cation exchange capacity and P also explained production variation. The liana load variable was only weakly significant for explaining production variation, and there were no direct significant effects of liana cutting. Cutting, however, did improve crown forms\u2014another highly significant model variable. This, coupled with a weakly significant interaction of liana cutting by year, suggests that liana cutting could improve production ove